===Etymology===
From Late {{inh|en|enm|marchaundising|t=commerce, trading; commodities, goods; (''plural'') dealings with other persons}}{{nb...|marchandising, marchaundisinge, marchaundisyng, marchaundisynge|otherforms=1}},<ref>{{R:MED Online|entry=marchaundīsing(e|pos=ger|id=MED26875}}</ref> from {{m|enm|marchaundisen|t=to engage in commerce, traffic}}<ref>{{R:MED Online|entry=marchaundīsen|pos=v|id=MED26874}}</ref> + {{m|enm|-ing|pos={{glossary|suffix}} forming {{glossary|gerund}}s}}.<ref>{{R:MED Online|entry=-ing(e|pos=''suf.''(1)|noformat=1|id=MED22696}}</ref> {{m|enm||Marchaundisen}} is derived from {{m|enm|marchaundise|t=commerce, trading; buying, purchasing; business transaction, bargain, deal; agreement; trade, vocation; merchandise, goods, wares; possessions, wealth; reward; ability or right to carry on business; market; communication between God and humans; sale of indulgences; simony; paid advocate or orator (?)}},<ref>{{R:MED Online|entry=marchaundīse|pos=n|id=16587756}}</ref> + {{m|enm|-en|pos=suffix forming the {{glossary|infinitive}} of {{glossary|verb}}s}};<ref>{{R:MED Online|entry=-en|pos=''suf.''(3)|noformat=1|id=MED13518}}</ref> and {{m|enm||marchaundise}} from {{der|en|xno|marchaundise}} and {{der|en|fro|marcheandise}} (modern {{cog|fr|marchandise}}), from {{m|en|fro|marcheant|t=seller, vendor}} (ultimately from {{der|en|la|mercātus|t=buying and selling, trade, traffic; market; marketplace}}, possibly originally {{der|en|ett|-}}) + {{m|fro|-ise|pos=suffix forming {{glossary|feminine}} nouns, often denoting a quality or state}}. The English word is analysable as {{suffix|en|merchandise|ing|pos2=suffix forming {{glossary|noun}}s from verbs, denoting the act of doing something, an action, or the embodiment of an action|id2=gerund noun}}.<ref>{{R:OED Online|pos=n|id=116646|date=March 2022|nodot=1}}; {{R:Lexico|pos=n}}</ref>

